article.headline: Huskies' Simmons continues to heat up
article.linkText: Washington handles Oregon State with ease
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- Tre Simmons made it look easy -- again. Simmons matched a career high with 26 points, going 6-of-7 from 3-point range, and Jamaal Williams added a career-high 24 points to help No. 14 Washington beat Oregon State 108-68 on Saturday night. "He got it going out there," Williams said. "He's one of those players. When he gets in one of those grooves, he can hit six, seven or eight in a row. It's hard to stop." Oregon State coach Jay John was hospitalized overnight after he left the arena at halftime after complaining of chest pains and shortness of breath. The 46-year-old coach was examined by an on-site doctor before paramedics were called. "He knows his own body and he said, 'I am going to go with a physician right now to the hospital. We are going to get things checked out. You guys go out and play your tails off, play with pride and try to get yourselves back into this ballgame,' " assistant coach Brian Loyd said. Simmons was coming off his first career double-double -- 15 points and 12 rebounds -- in a 77-56 win over Oregon. He has shared or led the Huskies (15-2, 5-1 Pac-10) in scoring in five of the last six games. This time, Simmons rebounded from a 3-of-8 shooting effort in the first half. "I was saying to myself that I'm a better shooter than that," he said. "I just followed through. I talked myself into that." And Simmons was just part of the Huskies' high-wire show. Nate Robinson had 15 points, eight rebounds and eight assists as Washington extended its home winning streak to 17 games and tied a 20-year-old school record with 11 straight Pac-10 wins at home. Bobby Jones added 15 points and seven rebounds for the Huskies, who are off to their best start in 29 years. "It's good when you can address your team and not have a lot of complaints," Washington coach Lorenzo Romar said. "There wasn't a whole lot we could say except to praise our guys." Nick DeWitz led Oregon State (10-6, 2-3) with 17 points and nine rebounds, while J.S. Nash scored 12 in his return from a one-game disciplinary absence. John shuffled his starters, putting a quicker lineup on the floor in a pre-emptive strike against Washington's quick feet, turnover-fueled defense and fluid fast-break offense. It only delayed the inevitable. Instead of falling behind right after tipoff, as Oregon did two nights ago, the Beavers led early, going ahead 12-8 and 17-14 through the first 8 minutes. Then the Huskies tightened the defense and forced seven turnovers during a 24-0 run. All told, the Huskies outscored Oregon State 30-2 over a span of 8:50 and kept them without any points for 7:52. "We'll see what happens next time if we get a lead, but it has been a process," Romar said. "It takes a while for the medicine to kick in and hopefully that's happening now. We've got to be consistent with it, though." The Huskies made it a playground contest. The burst started when Robinson soared through the lane to tip in a missed 3-point try by Will Conroy. Robinson added a jumper, Jones scored twice on feeds from Robinson and then threw down a fast-break dunk. Williams scored twice to put the Huskies ahead 44-22, and the rout was on. "I made a few shots early," Williams said. "Coach started to see that I had it going. He kept calling my number." John didn't come out for the second half, but the Beavers seemed focused and determined. They cut it to 51-30 in the opening moments after two quick baskets by David Lucas. The Huskies hit hard when they answered, using a 14-4 run to erase any doubt about the outcome. Simmons, who swished a 3-pointer just before halftime, made a string of three straight 3-pointers at one stretch, and soon the lead was 85-45. "We wanted to come out and get that win for coach because we didn't know what would happen to him," Lucas said. "Then we went out there and got beat even worse."
